<p>In court filings, NGP downplayed Pearlmanâ€™s partisanship, arguing instead that Aristotle, whose revenues had actually increased from $8 million to $14 million during the period of NGPâ€™s alleged misconduct, couldnâ€™t prove it was harmed. Even if customers switched, NGP argued, it was because NGP offered a better product, not because of its ideology.</p>
